My older gym boomer friend unironically talks to me about bodybuilding like Bushido, he says stuff like: "I see you are already on the path and there is no going back now, I can give you tips, but the path is only yours to walk, you must learn to listen to what your body says..."

None of you have any idea just how hype it is to hear a middle-aged Eastern European man give you mystical advice about lifting and "The Path that you must walk alone" between biceps sets, I feel ready to go and slaughter a dragon St. George style after the workout.

I like how unmistakably this was drawn by a woman, the Pseudo-Gollum cave creature is large and crude, but cute-dumb and cartoonishly confused, the little hobbit is small yet brave and serious in his little standoff. I think in many ways this expresses the daily femoid experience
Not even making a #MaleFeminist joke but like it's just the most female minded possible interpretation of the Tolkien scene

Like this is how girls see themselves when they have to go to the store to buy groceries or like talk to some bureaucrat type guy about some document everyday thing, a small creature being brave in the face of large looming scary but benign beings towering over them unknowingly

The Yojimbo film probably has the best depiction of late day warrior-aristocracy, the wandering ronin both repulsed by the weakness and vice of the commoners yet reluctantly ready to throw his life away to fix their trouble. Disgust and absolute compassion crashing w/ each other.

He's nauseated to the core at the peasant who had his wife stolen by the mafia boss and turned into a cuck and his inability to do anything, but also his instincts force him to slaughter a hundred men to solve the situation. He's unable to control his compulsion to restore order.

Sanjuro is the man alienated from his own aristocracy, unable to understand his powerful desire to help others and sacrifice his life for them readily, yet driven by this compulsion into absolute action like an animal by instinct. It's the only thing he can do, his blood beckons.
You will absolutely love it

Reading a short fragment about Matt Talbot, the Irish ascetic, that a friend published on his website and I am once again struck by how all saints, hermits, etc. tend to replace their pillow with a stone, a block of wood, a crude object when they want to mortificate their flesh.

A modern man's inclinations if he wished to impose physical hardship on himself and crucify his body for spiritual reasons by sleeping on a hard wooden plank, cold ground, etc. would be to just sleep with no pillow, but ascetics always use a pillow of stone, a log, metal anvil,..
